<section xml:id="Span">
  <title>Span</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A point <m>\mathbf{P}</m> is said to be a
        <term>linear combination of the points</term>:
        <m>\mathbf{P}_1 , \mathbf{P}_2,\ldots,\mathbf{P}_n</m> if
        <m>\mathbf{P} = t_1\mathbf{P}_1+ t_2\mathbf{P}_2+ \cdots+ t_n\mathbf{P}_n</m> for some list of real numbers <m>t_i</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The set of all linear combinations using points from a non-empty set
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\mathbb{S}=\{ \mathbf{P}_1, \mathbf{P}_2, \ldots, \mathbf{P}_n \}</m> is called the <term>span</term>
        of <m>\mathbb{S}</m>, and written:
        <me>
          span\mathbb{S} = \{\ t_1\mathbf{P}_1+t_2\mathbf{P}_2+\cdots+t_n\mathbf{P}_n\ | \; t_i  \in \mathbb{R}\ \}
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A set <m>\mathbb{S}</m> of points in
        <m>\mathbb{L}</m> is said to <term>span</term>
        <m>\mathbb{L}</m> if <m>span\mathbb{S}=\mathbb{L}</m>.
        This means that every point in
        <m>\mathbb{L}</m> is a linear combination of the points in <m>\mathbb{S}</m>.
        (Note: Span has again been defined as a noun and as a verb.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Describe the span of <m>\mathbb{S} = \{ \ot{1}{1}{0},\ot{0}{0}{1}\}</m>.
        Does <m>\mathbb{S}</m> span <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Does <m>\mathbb{S} = \{ x,x^2\}</m> span <m>\mathbb{P}_3</m>?
        If not, find a set that does.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find two different sets that span <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <theorem xml:id="spanS_is_subspace">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>\mathbb{S}</m> is a nonempty subset of a linear space <m>\mathbb{L}</m>,
        then <m>span\mathbb{S}</m> is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{L}</m>.
        Moreover, <m>span\mathbb{S}</m> is the smallest subspace of
        <m>\mathbb{L}</m> containing <m>\mathbb{S}</m>, in other words,
        any subspace of <m>\mathbb{L}</m> containing
        <m>\mathbb{S}</m> must also contain <m>span\mathbb{S}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <question>
  <p>
    What definition for <m>span\{\}</m> would make <xref ref="spanS_is_subspace"/> true without the condition that <m>\mathbb{S}</m> be non-empty?
  </p>
  </question>
</section>